1. Basic Linux Commands
Description: Introduction to the Ubuntu terminal environment. This covers file navigation (ls, cd, pwd), file manipulation (touch, cp, mv, rm), and directory management (mkdir).
A collection of essential Linux commands for beginners and professionals.

##  Navigation & File Management
- `pwd`: Print working directory.
- `ls -la`: List files with hidden items and permissions.
- `cd <path>`: Change directory.
- `mkdir <name>`: Create a directory.
- `touch <file>`: Create an empty file.
- `cp <src> <dest>`: Copy file/folder.
- `mv <src> <dest>`: Move or rename.
- `rm -rf <path>`: Remove recursively and forcefully.

## File Operations
- `cat <file>`: Print file content.
- `grep "pattern" <file>`: Search for text.
- `tail -f <file>`: Output the last part of a file (live).
- `nano` / `vi`: Terminal editors.

##  Permissions & System
- `chmod 755 <file>`: Set read/write/execute permissions.
- `chown user:group <file>`: Change ownership.
- `sudo`: Run with root privileges.
- `df -h`: Disk usage.
- `top`: System monitor.
